<FIRST>u i AM-Honduras 3rdLd-Writethru a0783 11-26 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0783,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honduran Voting Tranquil; Party Organizations At Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates grafs 2-5 with late results and voter turnout. Pickup
6th graf: Honduras is sandwiched...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition candidate Rafael
Leonardo Callejas took the lead Sunday in early returns as
Hondurans voted in the nation's third free presidential election of
the decade.
   Initial unofficial returns representing about 9 percent of the
precincts gave National Party candidate Callegas 89,360 votes to
79,445 for Carlos Flores, running for the governing Liberal Party.
The returns were broadcast by Honduran television.
   ``The people want to vote, and it makes me proud to be a
Honduran today,'' Callejas said shortly before the polls closed at
6 p.m.
   Surveys had indicated Callejas was a slight favorite.
   Election day was peaceful and officials placed the voter turnout
at about 85 percent. People went to the polls in flag-decked
trucks, buses and cars and on foot and horseback.
   Honduras is sandwiched between civil wars in El Salvador and
Nicaragua, and a formidable task for the new president will be how
to deal with thousands of Nicaraguan rebels living in border bases
in Honduras and a half million war refugees.
   Flores said in a radio interview before the vote tally began,
``We are very optimistic. We're getting a very good turnout among
our supporters.''
   Flores, 39, is publisher of La Tribuna, one of the nation's
leading newspapers, and was trained as an engineer at Louisiana
State University. His wife, Mary, is a U.S. citizen.
   Callejas, 46, comes from a landowning family and was trained as
an agricultural economist at Mississippi State University.
   If Callejas takes office for a four-year term Jan. 27, it will
mark the first transition of power to an opposition party since
1932. Sunday's was also the nation's third free presidential
election of the decade, after years of military-dominated rule.
   Both major candidates have relatively conservative economic
views and pro-U.S. foreign policies, although both also agree that
U.S.-supported Nicaraguan rebels should move out of Honduras.
However, neither has an idea for getting them to leave.
   Two other candidates, Enrique Aguilar Paz of the Social
Democrats and Efrain Diaz Arrivillaga of the Cristian Democrats,
had loyal but small followings.
   Also at stake were three vice presidential posts, a 128-seat
unicameral congress and 289 mayoralties. Voting was by party slate,
with no ticket splitting allowed.
   The major issue in the campaign was the bad economy and
unpopular incumbent President Jose Azcona Hoyo's weak Liberal
government. Azcona, elected in 1985, is barred by law from seeking
another term.
   Half a million refugees fleeing civil wars in neighboring El
Salvador and Nicaragua have sharpened economic problems that
include per capita income of only about $500 a year, high
unemployment and inflation, and little industry.
   More than 2.2 million people were registered, but voting was
concentrated at a few locations, and many in the countryside had to
travel more than 20 miles to cast ballots.
   Because turnout was considered vital in a nation where party
loyalty runs deep, the parties launched intense get-out-the-vote
efforts.
   Pickup trucks and leased buses sported blue flags for Callejas,
red for Flores. Both parties set up centers where voters could
report and be taken to the correct voting box.
   ``Some people can't read the room numbers,'' said Leila Martina
Vargas, a National Party pollworker guiding voters in Kennedy, a
poor district of the capital.
   At the University of Honduras, five miles east of the capital,
more than 31,000 people were scheduled to vote at 104 polling boxes.
   ``It's peaceful now. We'll see what it's like when we do the
count at six,'' joked Glenda Yolanda Molina Ortiz, a National Party
poll worker, drawing a laugh from other poll watchers.
   International observers said the biggest problem seen so far was
bureaucratic _ about 50,000 people were missing their registration
cards or had the wrong ones.
   Anti-fraud measures included glass boxes to prevent ballot
stuffing as well as a plan to count and report the vote quickly
using fax machines, to cut out the delays that might permit
fiddling with results.
   Wide coverage by the nation's aggressive radio and television
stations was also expected to reduce fraud.
   A military government fell in 1982, and Azcona was elected over
Callejas in 1985 under a now-discarded procedure that gave Azcona
victory even though he had 225,000 fewer votes.
   Azcona won because votes that went to three other Liberal
candidates were added to his column. This year, Flores beat three
challengers in a primary; Callejas faced no challenge.
</TEXT>
