<FIRST>u i BC-Czechoslovakia 2ndLd-Writethru a0630 11-26 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Czechoslovakia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0630,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Opens Talks with Opposition in Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with details from talks, Adamec
to address rally. Pickup 4th graf, `Sunday's discussions...'; subs 9th
graf, `His talks ...' to UPDATE with 2 grafs with Adamec comments on general
strike.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Premier Ladislav Adamec
opened unprecedented talks Sunday with opposition leaders in an
attempt to stem Czechoslovakia's mounting political crisis.
   Adamec met with playwright Vaclav Havel and eight other members
of the Civic Forum that has mobilized hundreds of thousands of
people in pro-democracy protests over the past week.
   It was the first time top government leaders of the Communist
regime have met with a delegation of dissidents. On Tuesday, Adamec
met with a group that included some opposition leaders.
   Havel presented opposition demands and the two sides agreed to
meet again Tuesday, government spokesman Miroslav Pavel said after
the one-hour talks.
   The opposition also demanded a parliamentary investigation of
the Nov. 17 police attack on peaceful demonstrators in downtown
Prague, complete press freedom and the release of more political
prisoners, Pavel said.
   Adamec planned to speak later Sunday to a mass rally by the
opposition, which drew half a million to a similar protest Saturday
in Prague.
   Sunday's discussions opened in a chandelier-lit salon at an
elegant Prague restaurant and ballroom complex. There was applause
as Adamec rose and shook hands with Havel across a table decorated
with a small red, white and blue Czechoslovak flag.
   Three other ministers and Bohuslav Kucera, head of the
Communist-allied Socialist Party that is now showing increasing
independence, joined Adamec on the government delegation.
   The Civic Forum delegation included prominent dissident Vaclav
Maly, a banned Roman Catholic priest; and two figures who played a
key mediation role over the past week, composer Mihal Kocab and
journalist Mihal Horacek.
   The meeting, preceded by a Civic Forum meeting with the official
Communist youth movement, was part of a frenzied attempt by
Communist authorities to deal with growing demands for democracy
and avert a two-hour general strike Monday.
   Havel said on Saturday that the general strike would go ahead as
planned. He described it as a national referendum on whether
one-party rule should continue in Czechoslovakia.
   Pavel quoted Adamec as saying the general strike ``is a reality
we can hardly change now,'' but appealed to all sides to avoid
confrontation.
   Havel's talks with Adamec seemed intended to clarify the
situation before the Communist Party's policy-making Central
Committee holds its second emergency session in three days later
Sunday.
   On Friday, at a marathon 16-hour session, the Central Committee
tried to stem the crisis by dumping party chief Milos Jakes and
other leaders associated with the hard-line policies pursued since
1968, when a Soviet-led Warsaw Pact invasion crushed the Prague
Spring reforms.
   But the shake-up was poorly received by Czechoslovaks, who
rallied in the hundreds of thousands Saturday to press their
demands for genuine democracy.
</TEXT>
