<FIRST>r i AM-Chile     11-26 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Attacks Leave One Dead, Blackout in Several Cities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas exploded a series of
bombs in Santiago overnight and early Sunday, killing a 16-year-old
boy and blacking out several cities in central Chile, police
reported.
   A leftist urban guerrilla gang called the Manuel Rodriguez
Patriotic Front claimed responsibility for the attacks, which took
place on President Augusto Pinochet's 74th birthday.
   In the most serious incident, police said 16-year-old Pablo
Robles was killed by a bomb that exploded shortly before midnight
in La Obra, a small village in the Andes foothills 16 miles
southeast of Santiago.
   Police said the bomb was planted near a monument honoring five
Pinochet bodyguards who were killed three years ago in an attempt
on the president's life.
   Police said Robles was walking with a friend when the explosion
occurred. The friend was hospitalized in serious condition.
   Other bombs blew out at least two electricity towers near
Santiago, blacking out several cities in central Chile including
the capital, where 4.5 million people live.
   Most power was back Sunday.
   At dawn, a powerful bomb exploded at Radio Mineria, a private
station in Santiago, leaving one technician slightly wounded and
causing heavy damage.
   Hernani Banda, the station's manager, said the bomb caused
severe damage to several offices. Radio Mineria went off the air
for several minutes after the blast.
   During the blackout, unidentified gunmen in a speeding car
sprayed the main entrance to the government's television station
with submachine-gun fire, police said. No one was wounded.
   A spokesman for the guerrilla group, who identified himself as
Jorge Salas, phoned local newspapers and radio stations to claim
responsibility for the bombings. Salas' voice is familiar to
reporters because he has called in similar situations in the past.
   The Manuel Rodriguez Front is the main guerrilla group fighting
Pinochet's 16-year-old regime. It has claimed responsibility for a
number of attacks on military and government targets, including the
attempt on Pinochet's life in September 1986.
   In a referendum Oct. 5, 1988, Chileans rejected Pinochet's bid
to extend his authoritarian rule until 1997. The 72-year-old army
commander was the sole candidate offered by the military. The vote
cleared the way for an open presidential election in December.
</TEXT>
