<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-89 1133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Ukraine-Protest     11-26 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ukraine-Protest,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tens of Thousands Ukrainians Demonstrate For Legalization of Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of Ukrainians demonstrated in
three cities Sunday to demand legalization of the Ukrainian
Catholic Church, banned since the rule of dictator Josef Stalin,
activists reported.
   The protest was timed to put pressure on Soviet authorities
before Friday's meeting between Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Pope John
Paul II at the Vatican, the first encounter between a Kremlin
leader and the head of Roman Catholicism.
   Anatoly Dotsenko, a Moscow-based member of the human rights
organizaton Ukrainian Helsinki Group, said the group's sources in
three cities _ Lvov, Chernovtsy and Ivano-Frankovsk _ reported
demonstrations attended by tens of thousands.
   The Rome-based head of the Ukrainian church, Cardinal Myroslav
Lubachivsky, urged a day of prayer and fasting Sunday for
legalization of the church.
   ``In the coming day, the fate of our church will be decided,''
he wrote in a letter to Ukrainian Catholics.
   The status of the church is expected to be a central topic in
the Vatican talks.
   Stalin merged the Ukrainian church with the Russian Orthodox
Church in 1946. The church continued to operate underground and in
the past two years Ukrainian Catholics have come out into the open
to demand official recognition from Moscow.
   According to Western estimates, there are more than 4 million
Catholics in the Ukraine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891126-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-89 1133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PoetrySearch     11-26 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poetry Search,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Byron Scholar Finds Last Piece of Puzzle in His Own Backyard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An English professor who searched
the world to complete a seven-volume collection of Byron's works
found one last poem just five minutes away from his office in a
University of Virginia library.
   As he was putting the finishing touches on the final book of his
collection of the English Romantic poet's works, he learned of an
early 19th-century American edition of George Gordon Byron's poems.
   ``This particular edition has not been noticed before. It was
published without the author's permission,'' said Professor Jerome
McGann.
   The volume contains a poem that McGann said has never been
included in an authorized Byron collection.
   McGann said the four-line verse, ``On the Regency,'' is one of
80 to 90 ``new'' poems in ``The Complete Poetical Works of Lord
Byron.''
   ``Some of these have never been known to exist, others have been
printed, but only in obscure books,'' McGann said. ``This is the
first complete Byron collection since the turn of the century, and
the first to contain these poems.''
   McGann said he began work on the Byron collection in 1970. He
had not known of the existence of the poem he found last week until
a colleague asked him recently if he thought the poem was
authentic, McGann said.
   The scholar said every piece included in the compilation was
painstakingly authenticated.
   Byron wrote from 1806 to 1824, and is remembered for such poems
as ``Don Juan'' and ``Childe Harold.''
   ``He fell out of favor for much of the 20th century, because his
work ran against the grain of the century's cherished ideas about
poetry,'' McGann said. ``Now, however, critics look at Bryon
differently. If there is any traditional British writer who would
be seen as being `post-modern,' it would surely be Byron.''
   Oxford University Press will publish McGann's seven-volume set
in the fall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
