<DOCNO> AP891126-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-89 1145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Ukrainian-Profiles     11-26 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ukrainian-Profiles,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Lives Show Strength of Banned Church</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ukrainian Catholics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LVOV, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ukrainian Catholic faith was banned 43
years ago, but several million people have kept it alive. Here are
sketches of three:
   _Ivan Gel, 52, spent 18 years in Soviet prison camps for
nationalist and human rights activities, and for his support of the
Ukrainian Catholic Church. He now heads the main organization
pressing for legal recognition.
   Gel says the church is an integral part of the ethnic character
of a people whose region has been traded and conquered by powerful
neighbors for centuries.
   _The Rev. Yevstavi Smal, 68, was a young monk in Lvov when the
church was banned in 1946. Like other priests who refused to join
the Russian Orthodox Church, he was sent to a prison camp.
   Smal served 10 years in the Soviet Far North and his chin
permanently rests on his chest because of a neck injury received in
the camp. Since his release in 1958, he has had no apartment of his
own and must depend on the charity of believers.
   He has been arrested 10 times for conducting private religious
services.
   ``We've already won morally,'' he said.
   _The Rev. Yaroslav Chukhny, 35, son of devout Ukrainian
Catholics, says he is among many young men from the Western Ukraine
who hid themselves in the Russian Orthodox clergy.
   After serving in one of Lvov's largest churches, the Cathedral
of the Transfiguration, for less than a year, he declared
allegiance to Rome on Oct. 29.
