<FIRST>r p AM-CommunionBan     11-26 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Communion Ban,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholic Pro-Choice Lawmaker Weathers Bishop's Communion Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK EVJE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state Senate race that started out ho-hum has
thrust one of the candidates into the national spotlight since a
bishop banned her from taking Communion because of her pro-choice
stance on abortion.
   The Roman Catholic bishop said candidate Lucy Killea's public
position is a blatant affront to the church.
   Killea has been besieged by interview requests from all over the
country and has made two national television appearances while
abortion rights advocates rally around her.
   Newspaper polls also show an overwhelming majority of Catholics
and non-Catholics in San Diego County object to Bishop Leo T.
Maher's sanction, the first of its kind in the nation against an
elected official and which many see as an unacceptable intrusion of
religion into politics.
   Killea, a Democrat and four-term assemblywoman from San Diego,
is on the Dec. 5 special election ballot for a seat vacated by a
resignation. Her Republican opponent is fellow Assemblywoman Carol
Bentley of El Cajon.
   Most political leaders agree the bishop's order significantly
enhances Killea's prospects of winning in a district where 49
percent of registered voters are Republican, compared to 38 percent
Democrats.
   However, Bentley believes her partisan advantage will offset any
adverse impact the controversy has on her campaign.
   ``This is still a Republican district, and I'm the Republican
candidate ... (but) the bishop certainly did take the campaign out
of our hands,'' she said.
   Bentley believes the winner will be the candidate whose
supporters are more motivated to go to the polls. That's why she
declined a request to appear with Killea on the Phil Donahue show
Nov. 20, believing her time was better spent campaigning.
   ``Personally, I don't care about my nationwide name ID _ I care
about what it is in the 39th District,'' she said.
   Killea says interviews and national television appearances have
cut into campaign time, but she's doing them because of the effect
the Communion ban might have on other Catholic elected officials
and potential politicians.
   She said she's afraid the bishop's order ``will prevent younger
people from getting involved in politics when they otherwise might
consider it.''
   Maher's order barring Killea from participating in Communion in
the Roman Catholic Church was issued one day after her campaign
began running television ads outlining the difference between her
stand on abortion and Bentley's.
   The ads talk about anti-abortion advocates ``dedicated to
turning back the clock on women's rights,'' and say there's a
danger that Californians once again may see ``painful, scary
back-alley abortions'' if those people get their way.
   Bentley, a Presbyterian, believes abortions should be permitted
only in cases of rape, incest or severe health complications for
the mother. She has kept her distance in the Killea-Maher rift,
calling it ``something between Lucy and her church.''
   Maher, head of the San Diego Diocese, notified Killea of the
sanction in a letter that said her advertisements and pro-choice
comments during the campaign ``are in complete contradiction to the
moral teachings of the Catholic Church.''
   A poll of San Diego County residents found 69 percent of
Catholics and 70 percent of non-Catholics disagreed with Maher's
order. Among Catholics, 72 percent of 405 people surveyed randomly
also said they disagree with the Catholic Church's stance on
abortion.
   The bishop denied any attempt to influence the race.
   ``If she hadn't run those ads, probably nothing would have been
done. But those ads are flagrantly contrary to the moral law of the
Catholic Church, and I think she brought this on herself,'' Maher
said.
</TEXT>
