<FIRST>r i AM-India-Fraud     11-26 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Fraud,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Little District Could Bring Down a Dynasty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-India, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an electoral version of the mouse
that roared, vote fraud in a rural backwater is threatening the
dynasty that has dominated the world's biggest democracy since
independence in 1947.
   The shenanigans in Amethi, the parliamentary district of Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi, also have highlighted political problems in
India, where criminals unite with politicians, distributing slush
funds and rigging votes.
   But the decision to call a re-vote in the 1,320-square-mile
dusty mix of rural poverty and boomtown also has given some cause
for hope.
   The Election Commission, which is supposed to be an independent
watchdog agency, reportedly was pressured by Gandhi's governing
Congress Party to reject calls for a re-vote in the district 350
miles southeast of New Delhi.
   Trouble began in Amethi on Wednesday, the first day of voting in
the national parliamentary election.
   An influential opposition leader, Sanjay Singh, was shot in the
stomach in a clash with Congress Party workers.
   Gandhi's opponent for the Parliament seat, Raj Mohan Gandhi,
alleged that police roughed him up when he went to a polling booth
to check reports of fraud. Raj Mohan Gandhi, who is unrelated to
the prime minister, is the grandson of Mohandas K. Gandhi, India's
beloved independence leader.
   The opposition demanded a re-poll, and the Election Commission
sent a four-man team to Amethi to investigate. The decision came
early Sunday after a marathon meeting: Re-voting was ordered for 98
booths in the district on Monday. Each precinct has about 1,000
voters.
   The commission also sacked two top police officers who had
supervised the vote.
   The decision dealt a stunning blow to the prestige of Gandhi,
the 45-year-old former airline pilot who became prime minister on a
wave of sympathy following the Oct. 31, 1984, assassination of his
mother, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi.
   Voting fraud is a common feature in Indian politics but never
had re-polling been ordered in the prime minister's own backyard.
   Gandhi's position already had been weakened by criticism of his
leadership and reports of high-level corruption in his government
stemming from a $1.4 billion weapons deal.
   In addition, the prime minister's Congress Party, which has
ruled India for all but 29 months since independence from British
rule, is facing the most cohesive challenge ever from a five-party
opposition coalition, the National Front.
   But even if Congress wins a majority in Parliament, many say
Gandhi's position as prime minister is in doubt.
   ``No one wants a prime minister who can't even control his own
constituency,'' said Bhabani Sen Gupta, a noted political
commentator.
</TEXT>
