<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-89 1336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-LincolnS&amp;L     11-26 1056</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lincoln S&amp;L,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Adjournment Offers Breathing Room to ``Keating 5''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An early adjournment by Congress this year is
giving the ``Keating 5'' senators who intervened with federal
regulators on behalf of the now-failed Lincoln Savings and Loan
Association a brief respite from the spotlight of formal
investigations.
   But even in the absence of public hearings, investigations
continue by two committees of Congress and several federal agencies
into how the California thrift owned by Phoenix millionaire Charles
H. Keating Jr. became possibly the biggest case of bank fraud in
history.
   And there is no shortage of opportunities for the major players
in the unfolding drama to make voluntary appearances.
   Two of the five accepted invitations to reiterate their defenses
on television Sunday, appearing along with one of their chief
accusers and the embattled federal regulator who is under growing
pressure to resign because of his role in dealing with the collapse
of Lincoln and scores of other S&amp;Ls.
   ``These are just the initial stage of an ongoing progress,''
House Banking Committee Chairman Henry B. Gonzalez said at the
conclusion last week of six hearings into why taxpayers are going
to have to pay up to $2.5 billion to depositors who trusted their
savings to Keating and his associates.
   According to regulators, that money _ in the form of S&amp;L
deposits insured by the federal government _ was lost to an
elaborate ``pyramid scheme'' of phoney real estate and other deals
perpetrated by Keating.
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, put the cost of the Lincoln bailout
alone at $50 out of the pockets of every American family.
   Named during 50 hours of testimony as accomplices in the scheme
_ knowing or unknowing _ were five U.S. senators, the nation's top
thrift regulators, former President Reagan's chief of staff, one of
the nation's most prestigious accounting firms and Federal Reserve
Board Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   ``Everybody that had a position of trust and responsibility has
a tremendous accounting to make to the American people still,''
said Gonazalez, a populist Texas Democrat who has taken a
let-the-chips-fall-where-they-may approach into his investigation
of what went wrong.
   M. Danny Wall, the chief S&amp;L regulator, said Sunday he has no
intention ``at this point'' of resigning as head of the Treasury
Department's Office of Thrift Supervision. President Bush two weeks
ago said he had not ruled out replacing Wall.
   Wall acknowledged on ABC's ``This Week With David Brinkley''
that ``we have in the final analysis made some mistakes,'' but
added that as the investigation proceeds, ``time will indeed be
kind to us.''
   Keating and a then-managing partner of the ``Big Eight''
accounting firm of Arthur Young &amp; Co. _ now Ernst &amp; Young _ that
served as Lincoln's auditor have declined to give a public
accounting.
   Of more than two dozen witnesses subpoenaed for the House
hearings, they were the only two to claim a Fifth Amendment
constitutional right to not testify on the grounds that what they
might say under oath could incriminate them.
   The five senators _ who received or solicited a total of $1.3
million in campaign and other political funds from Keating _ have
avoided testifying so far.
   Gonzalez and House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., said at the
opening of the hearings in October that it would be futile for the
House committee to subpoena the senators. Both cited precedents of
similar attempts in which senators simply refused to honor a
subpoena.
   And none of the five _ Sens. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; Donald W.
Riegle Jr., D-Mich.; John Glenn, D-Ohio; Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.,
and John McCain, R-Ariz. _ volunteered to subject themselves to a
grilling from their colleagues sitting on the other side of the
Capitol dome.
   All have acknowledged meeting with regulators from the Federal
Home Loan Bank Board in early 1987 on behalf of Keating _ ``their
friend and contributor'' _ as described by then-Bank Board Chairman
Edwin J. Gray, one of the meeting participants.
   Gray reiterated on the Brinkley show Sunday that the lawmakers
improperly pressured him as a favor to Keating. ``They were asking
me to withdraw a regulation for their friend,'' Gray said. ``I
said, `We're not going to do that.'''
   Glenn responded by repeating his strong contention that he did
nothing improper.
   ``Any implication that I have done something wrong in this case
is just flat wrong, and I resent it with every fiber in my being,''
Glenn said on the Brinkley show.
   McCain, appearing on the same show, likewise reiterated his
slightly less strident stance that ``it was a serious mistake on my
part'' to have not immediately made reimbursements for trips taken
on Keating's corporate plane, but that inquiries eventually will
clear him of any rule breaking.
   ``I did nothing that I wouldn't do for any major employer, or
economic factor, in my state,'' McCain said.
   Brinkley said Cranston, Riegle and DeConcini declined
invitations to appear on his show.
   At the time of the meetings on behalf of Keating, regulators had
been watching Lincoln evolve from a typical home mortgage lender
into the epitome of the ``high-flyer'' S&amp;Ls that prompted the need
for a $150 billion-plus taxpayer bailout of the industry this year.
   All five senators have said they violated no law nor rule of the
Senate. Nonetheless, the Senate Ethics Committee two weeks ago
appointed an outside counsel to investigate charges that their
intervention constituted a conflict of interest.
   The Senate's rules on such conflicts say that a senator cannot
``permit any compensation to accrue to his beneficial interest from
any source ... by virtue of influence improperly exerted from his
position as a member.''
   To one degree or another, all five senators claim the influence
they exerted was not improper. All maintain they have and will
continue to do the same thing for any constituent, regardless of
whether the constituent has contributed money to their political
causes.
   Meanwhile, Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell wants to use
the Lincoln controversy to reignite a long-stalled effort for
so-called campaign finance reform in which public tax dollars would
replace private contributions in financing political candidates'
election pitches to the voting public.
   ``Can an elected official receive something from another person,
anything of value, and retain his or her independence of
judgment?'' Mitchell asked. ``That's the issue that's raised by all
of this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
