<SECOND>AM-Felix Awards, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0654,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Film Takes Top Honor at European Film Awards</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd, ``The jury...'' to CORRECT that Ullmann Norwegian,
sted Swedish. Pickup 4th, ``Frenchman...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Landscape in the Mist,'' a movie about two boys
searching for their father, was named best film at this year's
European Film Awards, better known as the Felixes.
   The director, Theo Angelopoulos of Greece, received the prize
late Saturday at a theater on the Champs Elysees. The presentation
was the highlight of the second annual awards competition among
film makers from 27 countries.
   The jury, headed by Norwegian actress Liv Ullmann, chose the
film ahead of five other nominees: the Soviet Union's ``Little
Vera,'' Hungary's ``Eldorado,'' Iceland's ``Magnus,'' Portugal's
``Memories of the Yellow House,'' and Britain's ``High Hopes.''
   Frenchman Philippe Noiret won the best actor prize for
performances in the French film ``Life and Nothing Else'' and the
Franco-Italian ``Paradise Cinema.'' Those films also won special
prizes from the jury for artistic merit.
   Britain's Ruth Sheen claimed the best actress award for Mike
Leigh's ``High Hopes,'' a satirical look at Thatcherite England,
which also walked away with prizes for best supporting actress Edna
Dore and composer Andrew Dickson.
   The jury selected Hungarian Geza Boszormenyi as best director
for ``Eldorado.'' His film ``Recsk 1950-1953,'' made jointly with
Livia Gyarmathi, was chosen as best documentary.
   Special prizes of lifetime achievements went to Italian director
Federico Fellini and French producer Anatole Dauman.
   The European Film Awards were created by the Berlin Senate and
the European Cinema Society in 1988 as a European rival to the
American Academy Awards.
   The Felix statuettes awarded as prizes take their name from
French Riviera restaurant ``Le Felix'' in Cannes, where the idea of
the project was conceived.
</TEXT>
