<FIRST>r w AM-Freeman-Obit     11-26 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Freeman-Obit,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veteran AP Employee Dies In Sleep</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas J. Freeman, who worked for more than 40
years with the photo department for Associated Press in Washington,
died in his sleep on Thanksgiving evening. He was 63 years old.
   His family said the cause of death was not known.
   Freeman began his career as a mail clerk-messenger in 1948,
ambitious to be involved in the AP photo operation. While still a
messenger, the bureau photo chief, Burt Foster, described him this
way: ``He has done a large number of photographic assignments, with
excellent results. His camera work shows thought and news sense. He
is quick to understand a situation, a necessity for a
photographer.''
   Freeman moved up to become a photo printer and worked since 1972
as the Washington sales representative for Wide World Photos, which
handles commercial sales of AP photographs.
   Freeman is survived by four children. Services will be Wednesday
at St. Hughes Church in Greenbelt, Md.
</TEXT>
