<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Texts     11-26 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Texts,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Excerpts From Speeches by Havel, Adamec</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts, as translated
by The Associated Press, of addresses at an opposition rally in
Prague on Sunday:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Vaclav Havel, prominent dissident and leader of the Civic Forum
opposition group:
   One week ago, a people's movement began in Prague. For seven
days, Prague and the entire republic has been living through great
drama. After 40 years of totalitarian rule that manipulated them,
citizens have started to think and act freely.
   On behalf of the Civic Forum, I can announce that what we have
been calling for has happened: Dialogue has begun between the power
and the people. This morning, Premier Adamec has met with the Civic
Forum. On Tuesday we will meet again. I thank the premier for his
good will.
   Tomorrow we will show our determination to achieve democracy,
freedom and peace by a symbolic general strike. We ask you to make
sure that this strike will not threaten any vital functions of the
industry, the health of the people and lives. We do not want to
disrupt our economy. We want it to function better.
   We all ask what will come after the strike. The Civic Forum
suggests that the strike committees remain on permanent alert and
turn themselves into forums which will be the independent
representatives of the society throughout the republic.
   Civic Forum is ready to create a bridge for a peaceful path from
totalitarianism to civil freedom, which will later be guaranteed by
free elections. The Civic Forum is prepared to negotiate all stages
of the peaceful journey across this bridge.
   We know what we want _ truth, humanity and freedom. From now on,
we are all participating in the management of this country and we
are responsible for its fate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Premier Ladislav Adamec:
   I would like to thank the organizers of this rally for inviting
me. I will gladly explain my ideas, and I will listen to the
demands of any representatives of the public who are interested in
finding joint solutions of the problems that exist. That is why I
came here to join you.
   In only a few hours the general strike will begin. There is some
concern about what will happen and what the strike will bring. That
is why I proposed to look for an approach that will keep to a
minimum the damage it brings to the national economy.
   I am glad that all participants in the negotiations agree that
it should have a symbolic character. To state your views, it is not
necessary to strike for two hours. Two minutes would do.
   We must look for unity, without suspicion. We must try to
understand each other. That is why the government is prepared to
negotiate with everybody caring for the good of our country.
Throughout the country there is agreement in principle of the need
to speed up the reforms. Therefore it is necessary to limit the
social tension as soon as possible, to end strikes and
demonstrations.
   The enforcement of political demands must be in full agreement
with the efforts to improve the economic situation. This is what I
regard under the present conditions as the principal question.
</TEXT>
