<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary 1stLd-Writethru a0678 11-26 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0678,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarians Vote in Free Referendum On Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2 grafs for 5th pvs, `For the...' to UPDATE with enough
voting for referendum to be valid. Pick up 6th pvs, `Election officials...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After more than 40 years of Communist
rule, Hungarians voted freely Sunday on when and how to choose the
president of the new Hungarian republic.
   ``We wanted to take into our own hands the possibility to decide
on the people's future,'' said Imre Loerincz, a printer, after
voting.
   His words were echoed by many as they emerged from polling
stations set up in schools, hospitals and municipal buildings.
   ``After 40 years, it's high time'' people can vote freely on
issues important to them, said Erzsebet Nemere, a pensioner from a
working-class district of Budapest, the capital.
   State television said 53.6 percent of eligible voters in this
country of 10.6 million had cast ballots by late afternoon. Fifty
percent was needed for the referendum to be valid.
   Final results were expected sometime Monday or Tuesday.
   Election officials said many people were unfamiliar with voting
procedures and asked how to fill out the ballots. Some, still
conditioned from 40 years of one-party rule, even asked what
answers to give to the four questions on the ballot.
   The main issue was whether the first president of the new
republic should be chosen before or after free multiparty
parliamentary elections next year _ the first such elections since
the Communists consolidated power in 1948.
   The other three questions dealt with the ruling party's power:
whether the Workers' Militia, created to protect the Communists,
should be dissolved; whether the party should abolish its
representation at the workplace; and whether it should have to
account for its assets.
   Since the new republic was established Oct. 23 in a symbolic
rejection of Communist dominance, Parliament Speaker Matyas Szueros
has been acting president. The Socialist Party was created
following the dissolution of the Communist Party.
   The president commands the armed forces and can call elections
and dissolve Parliament.
   Parliament originally scheduled presidential elections this year
as part of an agreement between the ruling party and several
opposition groups.
   But the League of Free Democrats, the League of Young Democrats
and two other groups demanded the elections be held next year,
claiming the ruling party's candidate, Imre Pozsgay, would have an
advantage because he is already well known.
   They said the election should be put off until after the
parliamentary vote.
   The Socialists and other prominent opposition groups wanted the
president elected by direct vote before then.
   Many voters said they considered all four questions ``very
important,'' but some were cynical about the referendum.
   One man, currently unemployed, said many people he knew
considered the referendum ``ridiculous'' and did not intend to
vote. He declined to give his name.
   The referendum was marked by another first _ political
campaigning on television and radio.
   The four parties backing the postponed presidential election ran
TV spots each night for about 10 days before the vote at a cost of
$5,000 each for 15 seconds. The spots featured famous actors and
cultural figures.
   One spot showed a chick chipping through its shell and stepping
out into new life, saying, ``Vote for the future. Vote yes.''
   The Socialist Party also broadcast ads.
   The voting marked one of the first times voters in a Soviet bloc
country have gone to the polls in a binding nationwide referendum.
   In November 1987, the then-Communist government in Poland held a
referendum seeking public support for a radical program to make the
economy more market-oriented. Not enough people voted to make the
referendum law, although most of those who did cast ballots
supported the change.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
