<FIRST>r a AM-RapeAcquittal     11-26 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rape Acquittal,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newsaper: `Miniskirt' Victim Skirted Truth in Trial, Interviews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose alleged rapist was
acquitted in part because jurors implied she invited the attack by
wearing scanty clothes may have misled authorities and
interviewers, The Miami Herald reported Sunday.
   An investigation by the Herald uncovered inconsistencies in the
woman's statements and behavior during the trial, suggesting that
she lied when she denied working as a prostitute and attributed her
income to a trust fund from her father.
   The case aroused a storm of indignation when comments from the
jurors were published after the Oct. 6 acquittal of Steven Lord,
who faces similar rape charges in Georgia.
   The jury foreman, Roy Diamond, said that because the woman was
wearing a white lace miniskirt and no panties at the time of the
incident, ``We all felt she was asking for it.''
   The controversy led to demonstrations and pickets in front of
the Broward County Courthouse. The foreman later said the furor was
based on a misunderstanding of his comment.
   ``It meant sex, not rape,'' Diamond said. ``People heard it and
they just took it for the worst.'' He said her outfit was ``a
factor'' in the decision, but said the reason the jury did not
believe her was her inconsistencies on the witness stand.
   The 22-year-old victim gave interviews under several different
pseudonyms, appearing on ``Oprah Winfrey Show'' and ``Larry King
Live.'' She was also paid $3,000 by the British newspaper The Mail
for her story, the Herald reported in its Tropic magazine.
   Among the inconsistencies raised in the article:
   _ On the witness stand, the woman strongly denied Lord's
testimony that she was a prostitute or had agreed to have sex for
$100 when Lord met her in a restaurant parking lot at 3 a.m. Tropic
found, however, that she had worked at three massage parlors and
tanning salons that were raided by vice officers, although she was
never arrested.
   Two colleagues who spoke on condition of anonymity told the
newspaper the woman charged for sex both in and out of the salons.
   _ The woman explained her lack of employment by saying she had a
trust fund from her father, later claiming it had been looted by an
attorney. The attorney, Keith Nassetta, who faces similar charges
in other cases, says he never administered any trust fund for her.
   _ The woman testified she had spent the period before the 3 a.m.
incident with friends, but on the stand could not remember their
last names, how long she had spent with them or where they had gone.
   _ At the trial, she testified the first of several sexual
attacks occurred off the shoulder of Interstate 95. But she
initially told detective Tom White of the Indian River Sheriff's
Department that the first sex act occurred in a hotel parking lot _
as Lord had said.
   _ The woman at one point spent six days in jail after refusing
to honor subpoenas to testify in the case, and complained that she,
the victim, was being jailed instead of Lord. But police said she
gave them false names when they initially tried to serve subpoenas.
And check stubs showed she was working at a tanning salon _ and not
visiting California as she said _ at the time the subpoenas were
served. She shouted ``rape'' when officers handcuffed her to bring
her to jail, the Herald said.
   The woman refused to be interviewed for the story, the newspaper
said, but her attorney, Alexander Siegel, angrily denied Sunday
that his client is a prostitute.
   ``It's all innuendo,'' Siegel said. ``There's nothing in there
about my client, because there is nothing about my client. It's
character assassination done out of malice.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
