<DOCNO> AP891126-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-89 1733EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Boudin     11-26 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Boudin,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil Liberties Lawyer And Father Of Jailed Radical Dead at 77</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leonard B. Boudin, a civil liberties lawyer who
represented many prominent liberals and radicals and whose
daughter, now in jail, belonged to the radical Weather Underground,
has died at the age of 77.
   He died at St. Vincent's Hospital late Friday after a heart
attack.
   Boudin also represented one-time Teamsters leader Jimmy Hoffa
when he was banned from labor activities as a condition of his
prison release. He represented Cuba's interests in the United
States for the last 30 years and the Central Bank of Iran during
the Iran hostage crisis.
   His daughter, Kathy Boudin, 46, is serving a 20-year term in
state prison. She pleaded guilty to a murder charge for her
involvement in a 1981 Rockland County armored truck robbery in
which a guard and two police officers were killed.
   Before the robbery, Ms. Boudin had been wanted for questioning
about a 1970 bomb explosion in Greenwich Village that killed three
members of the Weather Underground, a militant offshoot of the
Students for a Democratic Society.
   Boudin defended many controversial clients involved in civil
liberties issues, including singer-actor Paul Robeson and Daniel
Ellsberg, who was charged with theft in connection with the
Pentagon Papers, classified documentation of the history of U.S.
involvement in Vietnam.
   He also represented Julian Bond, who was denied a seat in the
Georgia House of Representatives because of his opposition to the
Vietnam War, and Benjamin Spock, who was charged with conspiracy to
violate the Selective Service Act.
   In Boudin's best known legal victory, the U.S. Supreme Court
ruled in 1958 in Kent vs. Dulles that the State Department cannot
withhold passports for political reasons.
   In the late 1940s, Boudin and another lawyer, Victor Rabinowitz,
started their own labor law firm. They moved into civil liberties
law when an early provision of the Taft-Hartley Act forced union
leaders to swear under oath they were not Communists.
   Boudin was a visiting lecturer at the law schools of Harvard,
Stanford and the University of California at Berkeley.
   He is survived by his wife, Jean Roisman, his daughter, a son, a
brother and four grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891126-0046 </DOCNO>
