<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     11-26 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Activists Begin Paramilitary Patrols in Nablus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Groups of Palestinian activists armed with
assault rifles have begun organized patrols in the West Bank city
of Nablus to search for Palestinians they suspect of collaborating
with Israel, Arab reporters said Sunday.
   Members of two underground Palestinian gangs have been seen at
least twice patrolling alleys of Nablus' Old City, carrying lists
of suspected collaborators and questioning people, said the
reporters, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Trade Minister Ariel Sharon, meanwhile, proposed to annex parts
of the occupied lands with dense Jewish settlements as a prelude to
the Israeli-offered Palestinian elections.
   The hawkish Sharon, a leading opponent of Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir in the right-wing Likud bloc, said on Israel army radio that
otherwise, ``elections, in the form offered by our plan, would lead
to a Palestinian state.''
   Also Sunday, a riot erupted outside military court in the West
Bank town of Ramallah, reportedly after Palestinian detainees spit
and cursed at Israeli soldiers.
   A spokesman said soldiers used ``reasonable force'' to quell the
riot. He added that one soldier threw a grenade into a bus carrying
the detainees in order to deter them. The national news agency Itim
said soldiers beat the detainees with clubs and rifle butts.
   Elsewhere in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, 13 Palestinians were
reported shot and wounded in clashes with soldiers. The army said
it was checking reports of injuries.
   In Nablus, Arab reporters said gangs called the Black Panthers
and the Red Eagles began patrols through the Nablus casbah, or
market, late last week.
   In one case, the youths showed a Palestinian reporter a list
with at least 15 names of people suspected of cooperating with
Israel or committing moral offenses such as drug dealing or
prostitution.
   Palestinians have killed 150 of their fellow Arabs on such
charges during the 23-month-old Palestinian uprising. The toll
includes at least 23 murders in Nablus.
   The army has blamed the Red Eagles, loosely affiliated with the
Marxist PLO faction Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine,
for at least nine slayings.
   In some cases, Palestinians were tortured before they were
killed and their bodies were displayed in public as a warning to
local residents of the penalty for cooperating with Israel, the
army said.
   On Nov. 9, soldiers burst into a Nablus house where the Red
Eagles were believed hiding, gunning down an armed Palestinian
youth who was described as a commander of the group and arresting
five others, the military said.
   Arab reporters in Nablus say the army raid did not stop the
group.
   On Thursday, a lone man approached a woman shopping in a busy
market street and shot her in the head in full view of dozens of
shoppers. Later, members of the Black Panthers threatened to carry
out further slayings of alleged collaborators.
   On Saturday, the group kidnapped two Palestinians from the
Balata refugee camp and only released them after a severe beating,
Arab reporters said.
   The Black Panthers were initially affiliated with Yasser
Arafat's mainstream Fatah branch of the PLO, but they have ignored
direct radio messages from Arafat to stop the killings unless they
have specific orders.
   Neither group wears a uniform, but the Black Panthers wear
silver necklaces saying ``Al-Fahd al-Aswad,'' Arabic for ``black
panther,'' and the Red Eagles drape a red Palestinian headdress
around their shoulders.
</TEXT>
