<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovakia-Adamec     11-26 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Adamec,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caretaker Premier Emerges as Principal Figure in Upheaval</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Adamec pronounced AH-dah-mets.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asssociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia's premier, Ladislav
Adamec, has emerged as a central figure in the political ferment
triggered by massive demonstrations against Communist one-party
rule.
   Adamec's clever political maneuvering and clean background
helped build an image that made the 63-year-old veteran Communist
acceptable to the opposition as a negotiating partner. He was not
involved in the 1968 Soviet-led invasion that crushed the ``Prague
Spring'' reforms.
   Adamec drew both cheers and jeers from hundreds of thousands
when he joined opposition speakers at a rally Sunday, hours after
greeting dissident playwright Vaclav Havel with a historic
handshake at a closed-door meeting with the opposition.
   There seemed little doubt that he had maneuvered himself into a
position that could be decisive in helping find a way out of the
current crisis.
   A graduate of the Communist Party College and Prague's
University of Economics, Adamec was little known until he was named
head of the federal government 13 months ago.
   At an early stage, Adamec came out cautiously against repressing
dissent. ``Those who are blind and deaf to criticism have no right
to hold a leading position,'' he said shortly before taking office.
   He lived up to his words when he broke with the Communist
leadership in accepting a meeting last week with opposition
representatives.
   But hopes that he would lead a changeover in the party were
bashed after a party Central Committee meeting Friday.
   It was announced then that he had submitted his resignation late
last month both from the premiership and from the party's ruling
Politburo.
   Unconfirmed reports said his decision to quit followed growing
frustration with the orthodox policies of party chief Milos Jakes
and his associates. Most of them were demoted at the same Central
Committee meeting.
   ``There is no doubt that this (situation) could turn into a
dangerous conflict,'' Adamec warned the committee in a speech
released Sunday by the state-run news agency CTK. ``I am against
any onesidedness in political evaluation of forces which have
started to move ahead.''
   No permanent new premier has been named, leaving Adamec in
office for the time being and allowing him to defy the party
leadership's position of refusing contacts with the opposition.
   ``We made a positive assessment of Adamec's abilities,'' a
spokesman of the main opposition group, Civic Forum, told a weekend
news conference. He said so far, Adamec was the only one in the
leadership acceptable as a partner in a dialogue.
   On Sunday, the crowd chanted Adamec's name when he joined
Alexander Dubcek, leader of the crushed Prague Spring reform
movement, and opposition leaders in giving a speech.
   But he was booed when he suggested that a two-hour general
strike called by the opposition Monday be limited instead to two
minutes to prevent damage to the economy.
   ``It does not make much difference,'' observed one Czechoslovak
listener. ``Most people don't work anyway between noon and 2 p.m.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891126-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-89 1617EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Poland     11-26 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Poland,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Premier Prays Over the Body of Katyn Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATYN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki of
Poland led a prayer service Sunday in a snow-covered forest where
4,300 Polish officers were killed during World War II in a massacre
most Poles blame on the Soviets.
   Night had already fallen when Mazowiecki's voice sounded through
the forest 400 miles east of the Polish border.
   ``Let them lie in peace,'' he said as he stood in front of a
26-foot-tall wooden cross that marks the site of the slayings.
   For Mazowiecki and other members of his Solidarity-led
government, the Roman Catholic Mass at Katyn during their first
visit to the Soviet Union was a national obligation.
   In a speech at a Kremlin dinner on Friday, Mazowiecki said that
in order for there to be true friendship between the two nations,
the full story of the massacre must be told. In August, Mazowiecki
formed the first East bloc government not led by Communists, a move
the Soviets sanctioned.
   Mazowiecki told a Moscow news conference that he raised the
issue of Katyn when he met Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev on
Friday.
   The Polish leader said, ``Mikhail Gorbachev knows the meaning
this has for us, and we expect a clarification of this problem will
occur.''
   Mazowiecki laid a wreath in front of a long stone monument which
pays tribute to the Polish officers. The momument says, ``To the
victims of fascism, Polish officers shot by Hitlerites in 1941.''
   The Soviets still maintain the men were slain by the Nazis when
Hitler's army marched on Moscow. But most Poles and Western
historians believe the Soviet secret police massacred the officers
in the spring of 1940. Each man was killed with a single bullet to
the back of the head.
   With Poland in the Soviet orbit after World War II, it was taboo
to speak openly in Poland about Soviet responsibility until the
1980s, when the birth of Solidarity created a climate of openness.
   Recently, the Soviets, whose reforms have led to dramatic
political changes in Eastern Europe, have allowed Poles to travel
to Katyn. Earlier this year, a large wooden cross was erected
during a visit by Polish Primate Jozef Glemp.
   ``The victory is that we are here. It's a victory for us in
Poland and for those trying to organize a new life here,'' said
Aleksander Hauke-Ligowski, who led the Mass on Sunday.
   In the city of Smolensk, 17 miles from Katyn, a half-dozen local
human rights activists demonstrated their solidarity with the
Polish view of history. ``Open the truth about Katyn'' said one
banner. ``Mr. Mazowiecki, the Democratic Society of Smolensk
Welcomes You,'' said another.
   As members of Mazowiecki's delegation chatted in Russian with
the demonstrators, plainclothes police looked on but did not
interfere.
   Mazowiecki was accompanied by Soviet Vice Minister Nikolai
Larionov during the daylong visit to Zagorsk, Smolensk and finally
Katyn.
   During a visit to the monastery of Zagorsk, where Mazowiecki
knelt several times in silent prayer, he praised the Russian
Orthodox Church as a keeper of wisdom in the Soviet Union.
   A joint Soviet-Polish historical commission established by
Gorbachev and Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski in 1987 to
clear up historical blank spots has yet to deliver a final verdict
on the Katyn controversy.
   However, earlier this year the Polish side of the commission
concluded there is no reasonable doubt the Soviets were responsible.
   More than 15,000 Polish officers deported to three camps in the
Soviet Union in 1939 after the outbreak of World War II were never
heard from after the spring of 1940. The Katyn bodies were found by
the Germans in 1943, but traces of the other 11,000 men have never
been found.
   Mazowiecki was to travel to Leningrad on Monday from Moscow to
conclude his five-day Soviet visit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
