<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-89 1856EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RapeCharge     11-26 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rape Charge,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lack of Funds Means no Grand Jury Transcripts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The case against a Massachusetts state
police trooper charged with rape and attempted extortion may be
jeopardized by a lack of money to pay a stenographer, the defense
attorney said.
   John C. McBride, lawyer for suspended Trooper Robert Monteiro,
said he plans to file a motion to have the charges dismissed
because he is unable to get the transcript of grand jury
proceedings involving Monteiro.
   The grand jury stenographer has refused to produce any more
minutes of jury testimony until she is paid, but the chief
administrative judge's office and the Middlesex County District
Attorney's office say they haven't got the necessary funds.
   Superior Court Judge James McHugh said in court Tuesday he was
``frustrated that court proceedings are coming to a halt because
funds are not available to conduct the court's business.''
   ``It threatens a case involving significant public interest, as
well as others,'' McHugh said. ``It is absolutely impossible for
the defense or the prosecution to proceed without grand jury
minutes. They are constitutionally required and can't be produced.''
   Monteiro, 25, is charged with stopping four female motorists on
the Massachusetts Turnpike, raping two of them and trying to extort
sexual favors from the other two in return for neglecting to issue
traffic tickets. He was arraigned Sept. 5 on the rape charges.
   Deborah Christerson, who runs Christerson Court Reporting, the
firm that records and transcribes all county grand jury minutes,
said she will no longer provide transcripts until she was paid for
past work.
   According to The Boston Sunday Globe, Christerson is reportedly
owed for at least two months of work.
   Christerson has declined to comment on the matter.
   Edward Rapacki, first assistant district attorney for Middlesex
County, said his office would be willing to pay for the transcripts
if the state Legislature provided the money.
   The Monteiro case is scheduled back before McHugh on Friday, and
the judge has indicated he will rule under a state law that gives
him power to appoint a stenographer and order that copies of grand
jury minutes be made and paid for by the state.
</TEXT>
