<FIRST>r i AM-Gabon-Cannibalism     11-26 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gabon-Cannibalism,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Sentence for High Priest in Cannibalism Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Some contents may be offensive to some readers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIBREVILLE, Gabon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The high priest of a religious cult has
been sentenced to death for murder and leading cannibalism rites
where believers ate one of the sect's followers.
   Mba Ntem, 32, head of the animist sect based in a suburb of the
Gabonese capital, was found guilty and sentenced Saturday after a
two-day trial for murder, cannibalism and mutilation of a corpse.
   The Assises Court found Ntem's assistant, Raymond Mve Owono,
guilty of aiding in the cannibalism ceremonies by serving human
flesh to worshippers. He was sentenced to hard labor for life.
   Four other defendants received lesser penalties in connection
with the clubbing and stabbing death last year of teacher Andre
Ondo Ngong, a member of the cult. Ngong's mutilated body was
discovered in April 1988 in Oyem, a town in northern Gabon.
   After his arrest last year, the official newspaper Union
published a photo of Ntem with a knife in his teeth and a jar
containing pieces of a victim's tongue in his manacled hands.
   The cult was called ``Mvoe Ening,'' which the newspaper
translated as meaning the ``tranquil life.''
   In a ceremony led by Ntem, members of the cult ate Ngong's
stomach, liver, heart, lungs, tongue and genitals in what their
leader called a ``sacred plate,'' according to court testimony.
Some of the worshippers were unaware of the contents, Ntem told the
court.
   The court prohibited other details about the ritual and the cult
from being released. Animism is a loose religious belief popular in
central Africa and other parts of the world that a spirit or force
resides in every animate and inanimate object.
</TEXT>
