<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan     11-26 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockets Kill 18 In Kabul, Government Blames Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockets rained down on the Afghan
capital of Kabul Sunday, killing 18 people and wounding many
others, Radio Kabul reported.
   The broadcast monitored in Islamabad said the rockets were made
in the United States and fired by Moslem rebels battling the
Soviet-backed government for more than 10 years.
   ``Pakistan-supported extremists fired a number of U.S.-made
surface-to-surface rockets on Kabul, killing innocent citizens and
causing sorrow to many families,'' Radio Kabul said.
   It reported most of the casualties were inflicted by rockets
that hit a shopping center in downtown Kabul.
   Leaders of the anti-communist insurgents who hold positions in
the hills around Kabul say their rockets are aimed at military
targets and claim government forces fire missiles into the capital
in an effort to discredit the rebels.
   Government reports have said rocket attacks on Kabul since last
June killed 400 people.
   Guerrillas, supported by the United States, control much of the
countryside and rebel leaders have said their strategy is to cut
transportation routes to the major cities held by government forces.
   Rebels have frequently closed the 200-mile Salang highway, the
main route between Kabul and the Soviet Union.
   Western diplomats said last week that heavy fighting along the
highway has forced a delay in the government's planned winter
offensives.
   The Soviet Union sent troops into Afghanisan in 1979 to help the
government and had more than 100,000 military personnel in the
country before it began a pullout under a U.N.-brokered accord. It
said all of its combat units had withdrawn from the country by last
February.
</TEXT>
