<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Politics     11-26 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Politics,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Deputies To Challenge Communist Party Monopoly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of opposition deputies in the Soviet
congress agreed Sunday to challenge the Communist Party's legal
monopoly on power when the legislature reconvenes next month, an
observer said.
   He said the deputies, members of the Inter-Regional Group, also
want the group to be recognized as a formal opposition organization.
   The observer, who spoke with the condition he not be identified
by name, was interviewed after he attended a meeting of the
Inter-Regional Group's Coordination Council at Moscow State
University. The meeting was called to consider the agenda of the
Congress of People's Deputies that opens its winter session Dec. 12.
   Article 6 of the 1977 Soviet Constitution decrees the
Communist's Party's ``leading role'' in Soviet politics and society.
   Many reform deputies want that clause revoked and President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the Communist Party general secretary, has
said he would consider altering or eliminating it.
   Deputy Andrei D. Sakharov, the human rights activist and 1975
Nobel Peace laureate, has said democratization of Soviet society is
impossible unless Article 6 is abolished and other political
organizations are given the same legal and constitutional rights as
the Communist Party.
   The official Tass news agency said the decisions made by the
Coordination Council are tentative and must be considered by a full
meeting of the Inter-Regional Group scheduled for Dec. 9-10.
</TEXT>
