<FIRST>r a AM-DooDahParade     11-26 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Doo Dah Parade,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hibachi, Zsa Zsa Drill Teams Mark Wacky Parade To End Holiday Weekend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It had few rules, no queen and a Zsa Zsa
look-alike drill team, but about 50,000 people turned out Sunday
for the ``14th Occasional Pasadena Doo Dah Parade,'' a tweak on the
nose to the traditional Rose Parade.
   ``Buy your free programs here,'' yelled vendors as marchers
tried to outdo each other in tackiness and tastelessness. Among the
items of choice used by drill teams were briefcases, lawn furniture
and snow shovels.
   There was no formal judging.
   The parade highlight was the Great Zsa Zsa Drill Team, in which
several women and one burly man, all dressed as Zsa Zsa Gabor,
recreated the actress' infamous policeman-slapping incident with
men dressed as Beverly Hills motorcycle officers.
   Other crowd favorites were The Texas Chainsaw Massacre Drool
Team of the Living Dead Dishonor Guard, featuring marchers who
scared the crowd by toting running gas chain saws (no chains), and
several Exxon Valdez floats, including one operated by roller
skaters who kept falling down and yelling, ``The reef, the reef.''
   The Claude Rains Memorial 20-Man Invisible Marching Drill Team
had a drum major leading a stretch of empty pavement, while the
Barbecue &amp; Hibachi Marching Grill Team members banged on barbecues
with metal tongs.
   Bathroom fixtures were popular among entrants, including a Santa
Claus who drove a bike equipped with an outhouse, whose door would
open to expose a compromised Mrs. Claus. At least two other
entrants sat on toilets, while many band majors carried plungers.
   The Doo Dah parade, devised as an freewheeling alternative to
the stuffier Rose Parade, was first held Jan. 1, 1978, when the
Rose Parade was switched to Jan. 2 to avoid being held on a Sunday.
   Ever since, Doo Dah organizers have made it a point to hold the
parade on a Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
