<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Politics     11-26 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Politics,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher, Faced With Leadership Challenge, Slumps in Polls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, facing her first
party leadership challenge, would be defeated soundly if a national
election were held now, according to opinion polls published Sunday.
   One poll also indicated two-thirds of voters want Mrs. Thatcher
to resign before the next election, which must be held by mid-1992.
   The polls are among the worst for Mrs. Thatcher since she became
prime minister in 1979, and were published only days after she said
in an interview she's ready to fight two more general elections.
   Sir Anthony Meyer, the rank-and-file legislator challenging Mrs.
Thatcher, warned of ``a painful process of internecine strife'' if
she does not step down.
   The Sunday Times of London poll showed the opposition Labor
Party with 51 percent of voter support, its highest rating in a
decade. The party's 14-point lead over the Conservatives' 37
percent is the biggest lead since 1980.
   A poll in the Observer put Labor at 47 percent and the
Conservatives at 36 percent. Both polls indicated remaining support
was divided among the two centrist parties, the Liberal Democrats
and Social Democratic Party, and other small parties.
   The Sunday Times said its figures would be enough to give Labor
a majority of more than 100 seats in the 650-seat House of Commons.
   The Observer poll said of the two-thirds of voters who wanted
Mrs. Thatcher to step down, 44 percent wanted her to go
immediately. Of the one-third of respondents identifying themselves
as Conservatives who think she should resign, 11 percent said it
should happen immediately.
   Mrs. Thatcher, 64, has swept the Conservatives to three
successive election victories and is the longest-serving British
prime minister this century.
   Her Conservative colleagues have routinely endorsed her
leadership since 1975 when she ousted former Prime Minister Edward
Heath. This year, for the first time, she faces a challenger.
   Meyer, a 69-year-old former diplomat, says he'll run against
Mrs. Thatcher for the party leadership unless a more senior Tory
steps forward. Meyer has acknowledged he is a stalking horse.
   Nominations for the party leadership close Thursday, and voting
is scheduled for Dec. 5. Under a complicated voting formula, Mrs.
Thatcher must get 57 percent of the votes to win outright. If she
does not, some more prominent candidate than Meyer would be
expected to enter the race in a second ballot.
   ``It's terrific what she's done during the last 10 years, but
it's so important to conserve those achievements and not put it all
at risk,'' Meyer said Sunday on Sky Television.
   The Sunday Times poll said former Defense Secretary Michael
Heseltine is the public's favorite to lead the party, with a 30
percent sounding compared with 22 percent for Mrs. Thatcher.
   Among Tories, Mrs. Thatcher came out ahead with 47 percent to
Heseltine's 23 percent. But that was a 10 percent drop for her from
the last sounding in September, and a similar gain from her former
Cabinet minister.
   Both polls were taken last week. The Times poll, conducted by
Market Opinion and Research International (MORI), surveyed 1,068
voters. The Observer poll, conducted by Harris, surveyed 1,037.
Neither gave any margin of error.
</TEXT>
