<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-89 2311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-HongKong     11-26 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Hong Kong,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Says Vietnam Charging Britain $620 for Each Returning Refugee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain will pay Vietnam $620 for each Vietnamese
refugee it forcibly repatriates on the first flight from Hong Kong,
the Financial Times reported Monday.
   The business daily, quoting officials in the Vietnamese capital
of Hanoi, said Britain and Vietnam signed a confidential agreement
about the payments Wednesday.
   ``The sum for further flights would have to be negotiated
separately, officials in Hanoi said,'' the newspaper said.
   There was no immediate from the Foreign Office in London.
   The report said the first repatriations will be by air before
Christmas, probably on a 120-seat Boeing 737 chartered by the Hong
Kong government. The first Vietnamese to be returned probably will
be ``some of the 40,000 held in camps who may well not qualify as
refugees,'' the Financial Times said.
   It said Hong Kong was considering chartering larger aircraft or
even ships to send thousands of Vietnamese boat people home.
   The London newspaper said: ``Vietnamese officials added that
among those people due to be returned were criminals `who would now
be forced to suffer the penalty' and single women with children
whose prospects in Vietnam would be very limited.' They questioned
whether the act of returning such people could be considered
humanitarian.''
   There has been criticism in Britain from lawmakers, civil rights
organizations and the news media of the government's intention to
repatriate thousands of boat people on grounds they are not
political refugees but illegal immigrants to this crowded British
colony.
   The United States also has been denounced for not responding to
British appeals to take some of the refugees while criticizing
Britain for the planned repatriations.
   The exodus of Vietnamese began after the U.S.-backed South
Vietnamese government was defeated by communist forces from North
Vietnam in 1975, but thousands have continued to flee their
homeland since then.
</TEXT>
