<HEAD>Three Foreign Photographers Held By Military, Then Released</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with photographers' nationalities.
Photos later published. Pickup 8th graf `The crew...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador-War, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military on Sunday detained
three foreign photographers, including two Americans, who took
pictures of an abandoned airplane that apparently carried supplies
to leftist rebels.
   Juana Anderson of The Associated Press, Dayna Smith of The
Washington Post and Daymon Hartley of the Detroit Free Press were
held for more than six hours for not having permission to be in a
zone where the plane was located.
   Hartley said he and the other two photographers were detained at
a roadblock while leaving the area. He and Smith are American,
while Ms. Anderson is Peruvian.
   ``They checked out press passes, then kept us there about an
hour,'' said Hartley.
   Hartley said the three were led to a nearby town, where they
were told they should have gotten permission to visit the area.
Then they were taken to Treasury Police headquarters in San
Salvador, the capital.
   ``One colonel said, `Welcome to the house where nobody returns,'
when we got to the Treasury Police headquarters,'' Hartley said.
   But shortly afterward, the trio was released when correspondents
from The Associated Press and The Washington Post arrived at
Treasury Police headquarters. Some of the photographs they took
were later published.
   The crew of the plane that was photographed apparently were able
to unload its cargo after landing in the southern part of the
country, but they were unable to take off either for lack of fuel
or other reasons, officials said. The crew set fire to the plane
and fled.
   Hartley said there were trenches dug near the abandoned plane
filled with charred debris.
   The abandoned plane was discovered after another plane crashed
in eastern El Salvador on Saturday. Army troops recovered mostly
Soviet weapons from that plane, including 25 shoulder-fired
surface-to-air missiles.
   The supplies apparently were intended for rebels of the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, who recently launched a
major offensive against Salvador's rightist government. At least
1,000 people died in that offensive.
</TEXT>
