<FIRST>r f AM-France-Airbus     11-26 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Airbus,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airbus Announces New Model</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOULOUSE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Airbus consortium plans to build a
new two-engine short- to medium-range aircraft able to carry 186
passengers, Airbus Industrie formally announced Sunday.
   The model A-321 will be an elongated version of the model A-320,
which carries 150 passengers. Ten companies have placed firm orders
for 107 of the planes, with options to buy 14 more, Airbus said.
   The consortium envisions building up to 1,300 of the aircraft,
with the first deliveries to take place in 1994.
   Price figures for the purchases was not immediately disclosed.
   Airbus first signaled its intention to build the A-321 at the
Paris Air Show in June, but postponed an official announcement
until airlines placed a certain number of orders.
   Airbus Industrie is a consortium of the companies Aerospatiale
of France, Messerschmitt-Boelkow-Bloehm GmbH of Germany, British
Aerospace PLC and Construcciones Aeronauticas SA of Spain.
</TEXT>
